################################################################################
INSTALLING AOCL BINARY PACKAGES
################################################################################

- Use the command tar -xvf <aocl-linux-<compiler>-5.1.0.tar.gz> to untar the package.

- Run the ./install.sh in <aocl-linux-<compiler>-5.1.0 to install the AOCL package 
   (all libraries) to the default INSTALL_PATH: /home/<username>/aocl/5.1.0/<compiler>,
   where the compiler value is aocc or gcc.
   ./install.sh
   - Use -h option for "USAGE" help to be printed with all the supported options.

- To install the AOCL package in a custom location, use the installer with the option:
   -t <CUSTOM_PATH>.
   For example, ./install.sh -t /home/<username>.

- Default behavior:
      - fftw is installed by default.
      - fftz will ONLY be installed if explicitly requested via -l fftz.
      - fftw and fftz cannot be installed together.
      - If you try to install both, you will get:
        Error: 'fftw' and 'fftz' cannot be installed simultaneously. Install only one of them, 
                and when installing each individually, choose a different target directory.
    
       Examples:
      ./install.sh                        # installs default set (includes fftw)
      ./install.sh -l fftw fftz           # Error: cannot install both fftw and fftz together
      ./install.sh -l blis libflame fftz -i ilp64

- The master installer can also be used to install individual library out of the master package.
    – To install a specific library, use the option -l followed by the library name.
      For example, ./install.sh -l blis
      The library names that have been used are da, fftw, libm, crypto, libmem, 
      blis, libflame, scalapack, rng, secrng, sparse, fftz, dlp, compression and utils.
    – You can also install the individual library in a path of your choice.
      For example, ./install.sh -t /home/amd -l blis

- To change the default library path to ILP64 / LP64
    – cd <AOCL INSTALL PATH>
    – bash set_aocl_interface_symlink.sh <ilp64/lp64>

Refer to the AOCL User Guide in "Chapter 3 - Installing AOCL" for detailed steps.
